'''Yabuiri''' (藪入り) or '''Yabu-iri''' was a traditional holiday in Japan during which {{ill|apprentices|ja|丁稚|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|maids|ja|女中|12=draft|12=draft}} who worked as live-in servants in {{ill|merchant houses|ja|商家|12=draft|12=draft}} were allowed to return home to visit their families. The holiday was observed on {{ill|Lunisolar January 16|ja|1月16日 (旧暦)|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Lunisolar July 16|ja|7月16日 (旧暦)|12=draft|12=draft}}. The July observance was also called "{{ill|Later Yabuiri|ja|後の藪入り|12=draft|12=draft}}" (''Nochi no Yabuiri'')<ref>{{kotobank|後の藪入り}}</ref>.

== Origins ==
The custom of Yabuiri became widespread among urban merchant families during the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|12=draft|12=draft}}. It is believed to have originally been a day when a {{ill|bride|ja|嫁|12=draft|12=draft}} in a {{ill|virilocal marriage|ja|嫁取り婚|12=draft|12=draft}} would return to her parents' home. However, as urbanization progressed, it evolved into a custom for apprentices and domestic workers<ref name="heibon">「国民百科事典7」平凡社　p292-293　1962nd year 6月15日初版発行</ref>. 

In some regions, particularly in {{ill|Kansai|ja|関西地方|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Kagoshima|ja|鹿児島|12=draft|12=draft}}, Yabuiri was known as '''O-yagenzo''' ('''親見参''', "Parent Visitation")<ref name="heibon" /><ref name="koubunkan">「日本民俗大辞典　下」p737　吉川弘文館 2000th year 3月10日1版発行</ref>. Since the holiday was observed on days ending in six, it was also referred to as '''Rokuiri''' ('''六入り''', "Six-entry") in Kansai<ref name="koubunkan" />.

The dates of {{ill|Lunisolar January 15|ja|1月15日 (旧暦)|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Koshōgatsu|ja|小正月|12=draft|12=draft}}, the "Little New Year") and {{ill|Lunisolar July 15|ja|7月15日 (旧暦)|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Obon|ja|お盆|12=draft|12=draft}}, the Festival of the Dead) were important festival days. The timing of Yabuiri allowed apprentices and maids to complete their duties at their workplaces before returning home to take part in family festivities<ref name="koubunkan" />. Over time, these dates also became associated with the belief that {{ill|Enma Daio|ja|閻魔大王|12=draft|12=draft}}, the King of Hell, would cease punishing the souls of the dead on these days. As a result, many {{ill|Enma halls|ja|閻魔堂|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Jūō halls|ja|十王堂|12=draft|12=draft}} would open their doors for special ceremonies, and {{ill|temple fairs|ja|縁日|12=draft|12=draft}} would be held<ref name="koubunkan" />.

== Evolution ==
On Yabuiri, the master of the household would give his servants gifts such as new {{ill|kimono|ja|着物|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|footwear|ja|履物|12=draft|12=draft}}, spending money, and souvenirs to take home<ref name="koubunkan" />. The servants would then return to their family homes to spend the day with their parents. For those who had traveled long distances for work or had reached adulthood and could not return home, the day was spent enjoying entertainment such as {{ill|kabuki|ja|芝居|12=draft|12=draft}} performances or shopping.

Since Yabuiri was closely tied to the New Year and Obon festivals, it continued to be observed after the {{ill|Meiji Restoration|ja|明治維新|12=draft|12=draft}}, even after the {{ill|Japanese calendar|ja|太陰暦|12=draft|12=draft}} was replaced by the {{ill|Gregorian calendar|ja|太陽暦|12=draft|12=draft}}. As Japan industrialized, the number of workers increased, making Yabuiri an even more significant event. On Yabuiri, bustling districts such as {{ill|Asakusa|ja|浅草|12=draft|12=draft}} were crowded with apprentices and workers enjoying their rare day off. The growing popularity of {{ill|motion pictures|ja|映画|12=draft|12=draft}} was also fueled by Yabuiri<ref name="koubunkan" />.

After {{ill|World War II|ja|第二次世界大戦|12=draft|12=draft}}, changes in labor laws such as the strengthening of the {{ill|Labour Standards Act|ja|労働基準法|12=draft|12=draft}} and the adoption of the {{ill|five-day workweek|ja|週休2日制|12=draft|12=draft}} led to the decline of Yabuiri. Instead, it was absorbed into the longer {{ill|New Year holidays|ja|正月休み|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Obon holidays|ja|盆休み|12=draft|12=draft}}, surviving mainly as the tradition of {{ill|returning home for the holidays|ja|帰省|12=draft|12=draft}}.

== Etymology and Cultural Influence ==
The origin of the term ''Yabuiri'' is unclear, and several theories exist. One theory suggests that the name comes from the idea of returning to a "deep thicket" (藪, ''yabu'') in the countryside. Another suggests that it is derived from a corruption of ''Yado-iri'' (宿入り), meaning "returning to one's lodging"<ref name="koubunkan" /><ref>「日本人のしきたり」p55　飯倉晴武著　青春出版社 2003rd year 1月25日1版発行</ref>. A similar term, ''Yado-sagari'' (宿下がり), was used to describe women of the {{ill|Ōoku|ja|大奥|12=draft|12=draft}} returning home.

Yabuiri was a rare and precious holiday for servants, making it a major event in their lives. As a result, the custom was frequently referenced in literature, {{ill|haiku|ja|俳句|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Rakugo|ja|落語|12=draft|12=draft}} stories such as {{ill|Yabuiri (Rakugo)|ja|藪入り|12=draft|12=draft}}, formerly known as {{ill|Okama-sama|ja|お釜さま|12=draft|12=draft}}.

