On Yabuiri, the master of the household would give his servants gifts such as new {{ill|kimono|ja|着物|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|footwear|ja|履物|12=draft|12=draft}}, spending money, and souvenirs to take home<ref name="koubunkan" />. The servants would then return to their family homes to spend the day with their parents. For those who had traveled long distances for work or had reached adulthood and could not return home, the day was spent enjoying entertainment such as {{ill|kabuki|ja|芝居|12=draft|12=draft}} performances or shopping.

Since Yabuiri was closely tied to the New Year and Obon festivals, it continued to be observed after the {{ill|Meiji Restoration|ja|明治維新|12=draft|12=draft}}, even after the {{ill|Japanese calendar|ja|太陰暦|12=draft|12=draft}} was replaced by the {{ill|Gregorian calendar|1=Gregorian calendar|2=ja|3=グレゴリオ暦|4=fr|5=Calendrier grégorien|6=de|7=Gregorianischer Kalender|8=tl|9=Kalendaryong Gregoryano|10=ru|11=Григорианский календарь|ja|太陽暦|1=Solar calendar|2=ja|3=太陽暦|4=de|5=Solarkalender|6=fr|7=Calendrier solaire|8=it|9=Calendario solare|10=ru|11=Солнечный календарь|12=draft|12=draft}}. As Japan industrialized, the number of workers increased, making Yabuiri an even more significant event. On Yabuiri, bustling districts such as {{ill|Asakusa|ja|浅草|12=draft|12=draft}} were crowded with apprentices and workers enjoying their rare day off. The growing popularity of {{ill|motion pictures|ja|映画|12=draft|12=draft}} was also fueled by Yabuiri<ref name="koubunkan" />.

After {{ill|World War II|ja|第二次世界大戦|12=draft|12=draft}}, changes in labor laws such as the strengthening of the {{ill|Labour Standards Act|ja|労働基準法|12=draft|12=draft}} and the adoption of the {{ill|five-day workweek|ja|週休2日制|12=draft|12=draft}} led to the decline of Yabuiri. Instead, it was absorbed into the longer {{ill|New Year holidays|ja|正月休み|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Obon holidays|ja|盆休み|12=draft|12=draft}}, surviving mainly as the tradition of {{ill|returning home for the holidays|ja|帰省|12=draft|12=draft}}.

== Etymology and Cultural Influence ==
The origin of the term ''Yabuiri'' is unclear, and several theories exist. One theory suggests that the name comes from the idea of returning to a "deep thicket" (藪, ''yabu'') in the countryside. Another suggests that it is derived from a corruption of ''Yado-iri'' (宿入り), meaning "returning to one's lodging"<ref name="koubunkan" /><ref>「日本人のしきたり」p55　飯倉晴武著　青春出版社 2003rd year 1月25日1版発行</ref>. A similar term, ''Yado-sagari'' (宿下がり), was used to describe women of the {{ill|Ōoku|ja|大奥|12=draft|12=draft}} returning home.

Yabuiri was a rare and precious holiday for servants, making it a major event in their lives. As a result, the custom was frequently referenced in literature, {{ill|haiku|ja|俳句|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Rakugo|ja|落語|12=draft|12=draft}} stories such as {{ill|Yabuiri (Rakugo)|ja|藪入り|12=draft|12=draft}}, formerly known as {{ill|Okama-sama|ja|お釜さま|12=draft|12=draft}}.

