{{Otheruses|Yabuiri|落語|{{ill|Yabuiri (Rakugo)|ja|藪入り (落語)|qq=draft|qq=draft}}}}

'''Yabuiri''' (藪入り) or '''Yabu-iri''' was a traditional holiday in Japan during which {{ill|apprentices|ja|丁稚|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|maids|ja|女中|qq=draft|qq=draft}} who worked as live-in servants in {{ill|merchant houses|ja|商家|qq=draft|qq=draft}} were allowed to return home to visit their families. The holiday was observed on {{ill|Lunisolar January 16|ja|1月16日 (旧暦)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Lunisolar July 16|ja|7月16日 (旧暦)|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. The July observance was also called "{{ill|Later Yabuiri|ja|後の藪入り|qq=draft|qq=draft}}" (''Nochi no Yabuiri'')<ref>{{kotobank|後の藪入り}}</ref>.

== Origins ==
The custom of Yabuiri became widespread among urban merchant families during the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. It is believed to have originally been a day when a {{ill|bride|ja|嫁|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in a {{ill|virilocal marriage|ja|嫁取り婚|qq=draft|qq=draft}} would return to her parents' home. However, as urbanization progressed, it evolved into a custom for apprentices and domestic workers<ref name="heibon">「国民百科事典7」平凡社　p292-293　1962nd year 6月15日初版発行</ref>. 

In some regions, particularly in {{ill|Kansai|ja|関西地方|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Kagoshima|ja|鹿児島|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Yabuiri was known as '''O-yagenzo''' ('''親見参''', "Parent Visitation")<ref name="heibon" /><ref name="koubunkan">「日本民俗大辞典　下」p737　吉川弘文館 2000th year 3月10日1版発行</ref>. Since the holiday was observed on days ending in six, it was also referred to as '''Rokuiri''' ('''六入り''', "Six-entry") in Kansai<ref name="koubunkan" />.

The dates of {{ill|Lunisolar January 15|ja|1月15日 (旧暦)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Koshōgatsu|ja|小正月|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the "Little New Year") and {{ill|Lunisolar July 15|ja|7月15日 (旧暦)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Obon|ja|お盆|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the Festival of the Dead) were important festival days. The timing of Yabuiri allowed apprentices and maids to complete their duties at their workplaces before returning home to take part in family festivities<ref name="koubunkan" />. Over time, these dates also became associated with the belief that {{ill|Enma Daio|ja|閻魔大王|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the King of Hell, would cease punishing the souls of the dead on these days. As a result, many {{ill|Enma halls|ja|閻魔堂|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Jūō halls|ja|十王堂|qq=draft|qq=draft}} would open their doors for special ceremonies, and {{ill|temple fairs|ja|縁日|qq=draft|qq=draft}} would be held<ref name="koubunkan" />.

