After {{ill|World War II|ja|第二次世界大戦|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/World War II|qq=}}, changes in labor laws such as the strengthening of the {{ill|Labour Standards Act|ja|労働基準法|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Labour Standards Act|qq=}} and the adoption of the {{ill|five-day workweek|ja|週休2日制|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/five-day workweek|qq=}} led to the decline of Yabuiri. Instead, it was absorbed into the longer {{ill|New Year holidays|ja|正月休み|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/New Year holidays|qq=}} and {{ill|Obon holidays|ja|盆休み|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Obon holidays|qq=}}, surviving mainly as the tradition of {{ill|returning home for the holidays|ja|帰省|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/returning home for the holidays|qq=}}.

== Etymology and Cultural Influence ==
The origin of the term ''Yabuiri'' is unclear, and several theories exist. One theory suggests that the name comes from the idea of returning to a "deep thicket" (藪, ''yabu'') in the countryside. Another suggests that it is derived from a corruption of ''Yado-iri'' (宿入り), meaning "returning to one's lodging"<ref name="koubunkan" /><ref>「日本人のしきたり」p55　飯倉晴武著　青春出版社 2003rd year 1月25日1版発行</ref>. A similar term, ''Yado-sagari'' (宿下がり), was used to describe women of the {{ill|Ōoku|ja|大奥|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōoku|qq=}} returning home.

Yabuiri was a rare and precious holiday for servants, making it a major event in their lives. As a result, the custom was frequently referenced in literature, {{ill|haiku|ja|俳句|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/haiku|qq=}}, and {{ill|Rakugo|ja|落語|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Rakugo|qq=}} stories such as {{ill|Yabuiri (Rakugo)|ja|藪入り|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yabuiri (Rakugo)|qq=}}, formerly known as {{ill|Okama-sama|ja|お釜さま|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Okama-sama|qq=}}.

